"&#xa0;\nWritten evidence submitted by the London Borough of Hackney&#xa0;\nExecutive Summary &#xa0;\nIntroduction&#xa0;\nThe impact of the reform of housing support on Hackney residents▪\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nlarge average weekly shortfalls are occurring on new LHA claims from April 2012, notably on shared accommodation (£51pw), one beds (£32pw) and 3 beds (£3\n4pw)\n,\n▪\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nwell over 30% of new claims for 2 bed+ lettings between June and November 2012 had insufficient bedrooms\n,\n▪\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nBased on a 2010 baseline, there has been a 36% increase in the level of threatened and/or actual illegal eviction reported to Hackney Council\n,\n \n▪\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \namongst those on low incomes not eligible for LHA, officers are seeing evidence of increased use of sub-standard accommodation and severe overcrowding\n,\n▪\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nsingle people aged under 35 are moving out of borough.\n&#xa0;The response by Hackney Council and partners&#xa0;\nDiscretionary Housing Payments&#xa0;\nMeeting the demand for affordable housing&#xa0;\nHow the government can help address these issues&#xa0;\nConclusion27 September 2013\n&#xa0;\n"